localized.title: Is the 'sunshine cure' a real thing? - CrowdScience, BBC World Service podcast
localized.description:
CrowdScience investigates the conflicting scientific evidence around warm weather and wellbeing.

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

Imagine spending six months of every year living in total shade. That’s what life is like for residents of the Norwegian town of Rjukan, set so low in a valley that they see no direct sunshine at all from October to March. Marnie Chesterton heads there to hear about an ingenious solution: giant mirrors that beam rays down into the town square, where locals gather to feel the reflected heat. 

The man behind the project was motivated by a need for winter sun, but how much difference does it really make to our health and happiness? That’s the question posed by this week’s CrowdScience listener Michael, who has noticed living in the rainy Australian city of Melbourne is taking its toll. 

Many pensioners claim sunshine relieves aches and pains, as well as conditions like arthritis, but one of the biggest scientific studies found temperature actually has no impact on reported pain levels, while factors like air pressure and humidity may play a role. 

When it comes to our mood, it seems that spending time outside is more important than feeling the heat, and the optimum temperature for wellbeing is around cool 19 degrees centigrade, while excessive warm weather has been linked to an increase in violence and crime.

Check out more episodes of CrowdScience here: https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLz_B0PFGIn4cT4qluPKNtMmBAPPrpoxvT

Contributors:
Dr Anna Beukenhorst, University of Manchester
Professor Oscar Ybarra, University of Illinois
Professor Solomon Hsiang, University of California, Berkeley
Martin Andersen, artist

snippet.title: How birds travel thousands of miles every year - CrowdScience, BBC World Service Podcast
snippet.description:
Why do animals bother making such long and precarious migratory voyages? Is the lure of an arctic spring feast worth crossing an ocean for?

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

Why animals migrate - part 1 of a two-part CrowdScience investigation.

Wherever you are in the world, you are probably near an animal that has undertaken a remarkable migratory journey, be that a butterfly, bird or sea turtle. But what CrowdScience listener Moses in Kenya wants to know is, why they bother making such long and precarious voyages - and how they're able to reliably navigate over hundreds and sometimes even thousands of miles. In this first of two episodes, presenter Anand Jagatia travels to the Americas to meet the scientists finding and tracking these animals in order to solve the puzzle of where they go and why.

Deep in the lush and noisy Belizean jungle, Anand joins avian biologist Abidas who is collecting data on the beautiful birds that visit tropical forests to escape harsh winters. Here, using misting nets, Abidas and her team carefully catch birds to measure their health and status before tagging and releasing them so they can continue stocking up on jungle food. Anand finds out why having long term data on migrant birds can help in understanding why some birds, like the wood thrush, have been declining in their native homes further north.

Anand then jumps aboard a turtle boat in Florida where scientists from the Sea Turtle Conservancy have been collecting data on these dinosaur-like creatures. But finding them is harder it might seem. They move fast, so Anand accompanies the research team who are experienced in safely catching them, will he be lucky and find one of these magnificent creatures?

Presented by Anand Jagatia and produced by Melanie Brown

Contributors:
David Barrie – Navigator & author
Tim Guilford – University of Oxford
Abidas Ash – University of Belize
Kristen Ruegg – Colorado State University
David Godfrey – Sea Turtle Conservancy

Listen/Download: https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/w3ct1pry

snippet.title: Are you ever too old to have a baby? - The Global Story podcast, BBC World Service
snippet.description:
In countries across the world women are deciding to delay motherhood. Increased access to education, more career opportunities and less financial stability means that more and more women are having children later in life. 

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

But fewer babies now, could mean more economic pressures on the rest of us in the future. We explore this complex topic with the BBC's Population Correspondent Stephanie Hegarty and Professor of Reproductive Science at University College London, Joyce Harper.

snippet.title: Is democracy being restored or undermined in Poland? - World Questions, BBC World Service
snippet.description:
Is democracy being restored in Poland? Or undermined? After a bitter election a brand new government is making big changes. Politicians debate questions from a public audience.

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

World Questions Poland comes from the Royal Castle of Warsaw where Jonny Dymond chairs a debate with a panel of leading politicians who answer questions on the big issues facing the country, put to them by members of the public.  

The panel includes Mateusz Morawiecki, MP - former prime minister of Poland, vice president of the Law and Justice party; Senator Magdelena Biejat - deputy marshal of the senate, co-leader of Razem; Agnieszka Pomaska, MP - vice chair EU Affairs Committee, National Board member of Civic Platform; and Krzysztof Bosak, MP - co-leader of the Confederation and Independence Party.

00:30 Introduction
02:20 State TV was taken off air and staff were sacked after the new government accused the station of political bias. Was this action justified and democratic?  
10:00 How will Polish politicians tear down the rainbow curtain separating the country from the rest of the world? 
18:51 As Russia’s war against Ukraine moves into a third year, what is the endgame?

snippet.title: Is Serbia’s ruling party running a 'bot' army? - BBC Trending podcast, BBC World Service
snippet.description:
Over the summer, a mysterious Twitter persona published details of over 14,500 social media accounts - all of them controlled by real-life Serbian citizens, it's claimed. They stand accused of posting… whatever the president’s party tells them to.

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

It’s long been rumoured that Serbia’s ruling SNS party commands the online activity of a small army of citizens, dubbed ‘bots’ by the opposition. But this kind of list, naming and shaming thousands of ordinary Serbians, is unprecedented.

If true, their activity represents a form of political corruption according to Serbia’s public prosecutor. The government’s response has alarmed observers - it shrugged off the story, publishing instead a veiled tongue-in-cheek ‘admission’.

But who is behind the list, and can it be trusted? BBC Trending has analysed the data in an attempt to establish if the ‘bots’ are indeed real people. And whether their accounts show evidence of co-ordinated activity.

Featuring interviews gathered on the ground in Belgrade, we hear from opposition politicians, pro-democracy activists and a self-professed real-life ‘bot’. She tells us she trolled the president’s opponents under threat of losing her job – as a receptionist at a state-controlled electricity company in a small Serbian town.

00:00 Introduction
02:21 The SNS party and Aleksander Vucic
03:34 Jovana’s story as an online ‘bot’
06:13 ‘Bot’ list made public
08:48 CRTA – measuring and reporting about the quality of democracy in Serbia
11:15 BBC Serbian bureau data journalist, Lazar Covs
13:25 What do the social media platforms say?
13:57 Jovana speaks up
16:38 What does this tell us about Serbia’s political landscape?

Reporter: Sam Judah
Editor: Flora Carmichael
Additional reporting by: Grujica Andric, Lazar Covs, and Alison Benjamin.

snippet.title: What's behind India's viral videos? - BBC Extreme, BBC World Service
snippet.description:
Videos taken across India are going viral on social media. They show hordes of men harassing and even attacking young couples in the street.

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

The clips are accompanied by a hashtag #BhagwaLoveTrap - and have been inspired by an inflammatory narrative.

The theory suggests Hindu men are trying to seduce Muslim women and lure them away from their communities - but there’s scant evidence to support the idea.

Shruti Menon meets the Muslim activists pushing the idea of a "Bhagwa Love Trap", and asks what’s behind it.

And she hears from a Hindu leader who thinks the theory is nonsense, and claims the reverse is happening instead.

0:00 Introduction
1:17 Examples of Bhagwa Love Trap
3:08 Maryam was accused of falling victim to the Bhagwa Love Trap
4:48 Sara Ather wrote about the Bhagwa Love Trap
5:49 What some Hindu nationalists say
7:04 Meeting a Hindutva leader 
9:05 Interview with someone promoting the Bhagwa Love Trap theory
11:11 What is Love Jihad?
12:23 Shoaib Jamai, the man many see as responsible for popularising the Bhagwa Love Trap theory
14:30 Alok Kumar, head of the Hindutva organisation Vishwa Hindu Parishad
15:40 Looking at the evidence

Watch more episodes of our podcast series Extreme here. BBC Trending explores the ways social media is shaping behaviour and beliefs on the fringes of the internet - and in some cases, making it into the mainstream 👉🏽 https://studio.youtube.com/playlist/PLz_B0PFGIn4cd0kSwh2UhHlf17gxgZyV8/edit

Presenter: Shruti Menon

snippet.title: Is TikTok changing our behaviour? - BBC Trending podcast, BBC World Service
snippet.description:
TikTok started as an app for posting lip syncs and dance videos, but quickly developed into a platform where users can follow along world events, criminal investigations and social unrest in real time.

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

From frenzied speculation over true crime to vandalism and protests at schools, TikTok seems to be connected to harmful behaviour offline as the app draws in billions of eyeballs and spawns all kinds of content at scale and speed.

According to several company insiders, TikTok’s drive towards participation and maximising engagement has led to these frenzies. TikTok says their platform isn’t to blame, but is the app changing our behaviour?

00:00 Introduction

snippet.title: On the road with Mexico’s female truck drivers - BBC 100 Women, BBC World Service Documentaries
snippet.description:
Clara, Liszt and Paty are breaking gender barriers in the male-dominated cargo transport industry - they are some of Mexico’s traileras, women truck drivers travelling long distances on the country’s dangerous routes.

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

Robberies and abuse are part of the hazards they face in the job - but the traileras are determined to overcome adversity. BBC 100 Women rides with them as they work to make a better life for their families and change the face of the next generation of drivers in Latin America.
 
00:00 Introduction
01:37 Driving in a male-dominated industry where only 3% of drivers are women 
02:10 Clara’s story: “I didn’t know that it was violence”
05:14 Liszt’s story: “I would like to spend more time at home, but life is expensive”
08:10 Meeting Paty, the trainee
09:46 “I always dreamt of driving a red convertible”
11:53 Pit stop at La Lupita: “Roads are unsafe now” 
13:40 Held at gunpoint: The story of the robberies
17:29 How to stay safe at night
18:16 Hope: “Companies are giving women a chance, but there’s still work to do” 
20:48 Finally home

snippet.title: Greenland’s lost generation - BBC World Service Documentaries, 100 Women
snippet.description:
Greenland has been rocked by a scandal revealing a Danish campaign to curb its growing Inuit population from the mid 1960s to late 1970s.

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

Now being officially investigated, about 4,500 women had an intrauterine device, commonly known as coil, inserted - often against their will. BBC 100 Women goes to the heart of the scandal, meeting women who’ve begun piecing together reasons behind physical and mental trauma that they’d endured for decades in silence.

The BBC 100 Women team has a mission to address the under-representation of women in media. If you are interested in their content check out these playlists:

snippet.title: Rebel Wilson on her 'year of health' during the pandemic - 100 Women, BBC World Service
snippet.description:
Rebel Wilson made her name in Hollywood as a comedy actress, starring in female-led comedy hit Bridesmaids and the box-office success Pitch Perfect trilogy - the second in the franchise became the highest-grossing musical comedy of all time when it was released in 2015.

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

Now a producer and director, Wilson fought her way to the top in an industry dominated by men and ruled by beauty ideals. In an exclusive 100 Women interview with the BBC’s Nomia Iqbal, she reflects on what it means to be the "funny, fat girl", why she went on a "year of health" during the pandemic, and decided to speak openly about her fertility struggles.

The BBC 100 Women team has a mission to address the under-representation of women in media. If you are interested in their content check out these playlists: 

Watch more interviews with inspiring women in this playlist 👉🏽
https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLz_B0PFGIn4dhPgx8sYodX7xtdX7nHTmB

Interview by Nomia Iqbal. Produced by Valeria Perasso and Rebecca Thorn. Filmed by Peter Murtaugh. Edited by Holly Stimson.

snippet.title: Priyanka Chopra Jonas on body shaming, social media and pay parity - BBC World Service
snippet.description:
Priyanka Chopra Jonas never dreamt of becoming famous – but then she won the 2000 Miss World pageant which provided a “small-town girl” with a springboard for an international career. 

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

In an interview with BBC 100 Women’s Yogita Limaye, the Indian actress and producer speaks about body shaming, pay parity and the pressure social media can bring.

She says she was getting paid 10% of her male co-actor’s salary while starring in Bollywood movies, and it’s been only during her most recent acting engagements in Hollywood that she has seen the gender pay gap closing for her.
 
The BBC 100 Women team has a mission to address the under-representation of women in media. If you are interested in their content check out these playlists:

snippet.title: How brides spend less on their wedding dress - BBC World Service, Business Daily podcast
snippet.description:
In the UK, brides spend an average of £1,400 on a dress for the big day.

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

But inflation and the rising cost of living means that's starting to change. We look at the trend of spending less on wedding dresses - buying them ready-to-wear from a boutique in London, or even from a supermarket.

And we're in India where some brides are starting to spend less - not always easy when spending lavishly on weddings is often the expectation.

Produced and presented by Deborah Weitzmann with additional presenting from Devina Gupta.

In the UK, brides spend an average of £1,400 on a dress for the big day.

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

But inflation and the rising cost of living means that's starting to change. We look at the trend of spending less on wedding dresses - buying them ready-to-wear from a boutique in London, or even from a supermarket.

And we're in India where some brides are starting to spend less - not always easy when spending lavishly on weddings is often the expectation.

Produced and presented by Deborah Weitzmann with additional presenting from Devina Gupta.

snippet.title: Bad science: AI used to target kids with disinformation on YouTube - BBC World Service
snippet.description:
YouTube channels that use AI to make videos which include false science information are being recommended to children as “educational content”, the BBC’s Global Disinformation Team has found.

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

We identified over 50 channels in more than 20 languages using AI to create videos with pseudo-science or conspiracy theories. With millions of views in their channels, creators make money from placed ads.

YouTube says it is committed to removing misinformation from its platforms.

00:00 - What are “bad science” videos?
01:41 - How do we know they’re reaching children?
02:11 - Would kids believe these videos?
03:45 - How are they multiplying so fast?
04:24 - Stealing from other creators
06:07 - Making money from views
06:57 - Reveal
07:14 - What do educators think?
08:00 - YouTube’s reply
08:44 - Emerging threat

snippet.title: Women rewiring Hollywood's comedy circuit - The Conversation podcast, BBC World Service
snippet.description:
Kim Chakanetsa is in the heart of Los Angeles' comedy district to meet two stand-up comedians who recently opened their own venues.

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

Jiaoying Summers is a stand-up comedian, a social media star and the owner of The Hollywood Comedy Club and the Pasadena Comedy Club. Originally from China, she moved to the US when she was 18. She studied theatre and drama, but after director John Singleton failed her at an audition and suggested she should try comedy instead, she gave stand-up a go. She says comedy saved her life and helped her through her post-partum depression and her divorce.

Nthenya Ndunda is an actor and comedian who, in 2021, opened The Comedy Nook, a venue promoting the work of black artists. She was born in Kenya and grew up in Canada, and decided to open her business after her best friend passed away. Nthenya draws inspiration for her jokes from her personal experience as a black woman living in the US and as the mother of a one-year-old.

Check out more videos of women breaking taboos here: https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLz_B0PFGIn4chwVM2CcwuPeP2tnYIQpp8

snippet.title: Women in Hollywood: Who runs the film industry? - The Conversation podcast, BBC World Service
snippet.description:
There was an impressive list of female creatives on this year's Oscar nominees list – actors, producers, costume designers - but no female directors.

Click here to subscribe 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

In fact, in the Academy’s 94-year-history, only seven women have ever been nominated. Why is that? And what is getting in the way of achieving gender parity in filmmaking? Kim Chakanetsa travels to the heart of Hollywood to find out more.

Keri Putnam is a film executive and producer and the founder of Putnam Pictures. She served for 11 years as the CEO of the Sundance Institute which runs the Sundance Film Festival. Prior to that worked as a senior executive at Miramax and HBO. She is also the co-founder of Re-frame, an organisation providing mentorship and training to help women making it into the industry, and served three terms on the Women in Film Board of directors.

Stephanie Allain is a film Producer and writer and the newly-elected co-President of the Producers Guild of America, the first woman of colour to serve as PGA president. Stephanie was one of the original ReFrame ambassadors and served 3 terms on the WIF Board of Directors including nine years as Vice President. Stephanie was also the first Black woman to produce the Academy Awards in 2020. She runs her own company, Homegrown Pictures, which focuses on creating content by and about women and people of colour.

Check out more awesome women creating change here 👉🏽 https://bit.ly/3Wo1nu4

snippet.title: Trolls on Twitter - Trolled podcast, BBC World Service
snippet.description:
Since the world’s richest man Elon Musk bought Twitter last year, more than half the workforce has been sacked and scores of users previously banned for breaking Twitter’s rules were reinstated.

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

Marianna Spring investigates how Elon Musk is transforming one of the world’s most influential social media platforms. She speaks to former insiders and examines evidence that suggests trolling and hate are thriving under the new owner.

Check out more episodes of our podcast Trolled here: https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLz_B0PFGIn4eJ9sARkGWeEFYK5R58MOEB

snippet.title: Pro-junta trolls doxxing Burmese women - Trolled podcast, BBC World Service
snippet.description:
Warning: Contains crude language and threats of violence. 

Burmese women have been at the forefront of the resistance against the military junta ever since Myanmar lurched back into a dictatorship in 2021. 

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

Online, female activists and politicians have been fighting for their rights, gathering intel and strategising - hoping that one day Myanmar will return to democracy. But these women have also been on the receiving end of targeted online attacks which have leaked into the offline world. So who is behind these strategic hate campaigns and why are they doing it?

BBC Trending’s Reha Kansara investigates and unearths a network of pro-junta online trolls who dox and abuse women who oppose the regime. 

Check out more episodes of our BBC Trending podcast Trolled here: https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLz_B0PFGIn4eJ9sARkGWeEFYK5R58MOEB

snippet.title: A mother tells her daughter to ignore baby pressures - Dear Daughter podcast, BBC World Service
snippet.description:
Simone is from Mozambique and tells Namulanta that society puts a lot of pressure on women to have a baby.

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

Simone writes to her young daughter telling her: "You don’t need to give me a grandchild." They discuss the expectation that some parents place on women to provide them with grandchildren. She promises having children will be up to her daughter. She says in her letter: “Make your own decision.” 

Our podcast, Dear Daughter, features letters from parents to their children creating a "handbook to life".

Check out more episodes of our Dear Daughter podcast here: https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLz_B0PFGIn4fEIsDXCFFwPfjl8W3gwF_6

snippet.title: The mother writing to her daughter who is in a coma - Dear Daughter podcast, BBC World Service
snippet.description:
Namulanta meets with Isabel Allende, The "Queen of Letters", who reads what she wrote to her daughter, Paula, when she was in a coma.

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

The best-selling author also talks about writing, processing grief and a full garage. 

She then turned the letters into a book. She says writing “allowed me to understand what had happened and deal with it”. Isabel has a garage full of her daily correspondence with her own mother. 

Her novels include The House of the Spirits, City of the Beasts and Eva Luna. 

Isabel is reading an extract from her book "Paula."

Our podcast, Dear Daughter, features letters from parents to their children.

snippet.title: Like, Follow, Trafficked: Insta’s Fake Guru - BBC World Service Documentaries
snippet.description:
#BBCEye Investigations and #BBCNewsBrasil uncover the truth behind the rise of wellness influencer and spiritual life coach, Kat Torres, and the international search for her trafficked followers.

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

Former Brazilian model, wellness influencer and spiritual life coach Kat Torres was an inspiration and a lifeline to women all over the world. More than a million people on Instagram followed her extraordinary career trajectory from extreme poverty in Brazil, to a European modelling career and a life of luxury in the US.   
 
But behind the perfectly curated posts is a story of witchcraft, exploitation and human trafficking - a dark and secretive sorority that led to missing women and sent their families and the FBI on a desperate search to find them.
 
After months of investigations, a team from #BBCEye and https://www.youtube.com/user/BBCBrasil uncover a wellness empire built on half-truths and lies. This film tells the story of her enslaved followers and the heavy price they paid. snippet.title: Child labour behind global brands' best-selling perfumes - BBC World Service Documentaries
snippet.description:
A new investigation from BBC Eye takes you to the heart of the jasmine trade in Egypt, to reveal the dark secrets behind the perfume industry.

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

Children are working in dangerous conditions throughout the night, and pickers are often earning as little as a dollar a day, while huge profits are made by the giants in the perfume industry.  

Over half of the world’s supply of jasmine is produced in Egypt and this story reveals the true human cost of this precious flower, considered to be one of the most valuable ingredients used in some of the world's most iconic perfumes.  

Billion-dollar global brands, who use Egyptian jasmine in their perfumes, claim to have zero tolerance on child labour throughout their supply chains. But the BBC can reveal that in the 2023 jasmine harvest season, children - some as young as five years old - were working in the jasmine fields that were supplying these global brands through factories in Egypt.

snippet.title: Inside Gaza’s ambulances: Paramedics witness the horrors of war - BBC World Service Documentaries
snippet.description:
Within a week of the war starting, the Israel Defense Forces (IDF) dropped 6,000 bombs on northern Gaza - according to the IDF. Many of those killed or injured in the strikes are children, including newborn babies who are rushed to hospital. 

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

This film, shot by journalist Feras Al-Ajrami from Gaza, offers rare, intimate access to the work of the Palestinian Red Crescent [PRCS], who are the first to respond when civilians call 101, the Gaza emergency number. 

10,000 Palestinians are killed in a month, a figure the medics themselves help to inform, as they count the dead bodies they stretcher from buildings blasted to rubble. 

Gaza 101: Emergency Rescue, shows the extreme psychological toll on the PRCS crew, when three of their colleagues are killed by an IDF airstrike that destroys one of their ambulances. The IDF told the BBC they did not intentionally target the ambulance.

0:00 Pre-title
01:22 Gaza 101: Emergency Rescue 
02:32 Red Cross/Crescent volunteers
06:16 Early days of the war

11:52 “We want to live in peace”

snippet.title: How Nepal is saving its tigers - BBC World Service Documentaries
snippet.description:
In 2010, the Himalayan nation of Nepal was one of 13 countries to commit to doubling its wild tiger populations by 2022. In the decade since, Nepal is the only country to have achieved that goal. 

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

Over that time, other iconic species including rhinos and elephants have also seen an increase. What's behind the success? And what does it mean for the communities living with the tigers? The BBC's Asia editor Rebecca Henschke reports in "Return of the tigers" from Bardiya National Park.
 
Directed and filmed by: Kevin Kim
Produced by: Rajan Parajuli

snippet.title: The evolution of the Islamic State Group - The Global Jigsaw podcast, BBC World Service
snippet.description:
After a lull in activities, in 2024 the Islamic State Group claimed to be behind several major attacks, showing the world they haven’t gone away. 

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

Among them was the storming by gunmen of a Moscow concert hall. Ten years after the Islamist extremists declared the establishment of a caliphate, our Jihadist Media Monitoring Team considers the current capabilities and ambitions of the group that once ruled over a large territory in Iraq and Syria.
 
Broadcast on 15 June 2024

snippet.title: Sirimavo Bandaranaike: The world’s first woman prime minister - BBC World Service, Witness History
snippet.description:
Sirimavo Bandaranaike was elected the modern world’s first female head of government in 1960, when she became the prime minister of Sri Lanka, or Ceylon as it was known then.

She entered politics after the assassination of her husband just a year earlier.

snippet.description:
This is the story of Janessa Brazil – the woman whose face and body has unwittingly been used in romance scams and online fraud around the world, where catfish scammers use fake online profiles to lure victims into a relationship, sometimes to steal from them.

New Year’s Eve. Simon receives a message from a beautiful stranger, named Shirley: “Greetings… from my world to yours.” A digital flirtation begins. Then Shirley needs cash – fast. Has she any idea that she’s the bait in worldwide catfishing schemes?

snippet.title: Dars: The fight for Afghan girls' education - BBC World Service Documentaries
snippet.description:
When the Taliban took power in August 2021, they closed off access to formal education for girls aged 11 and over.  According to UNESCO, 80% of school-aged Afghan girls and young women, 2.5 million people, are now out of school.   

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

In response, the BBC World Service created “Dars” or “Lesson”, a TV and radio series in Pashto and Dari. Now, despite the challenges, four female BBC presenters who fled the country following the Taliban takeover are helping to bring education back to Afghan children.  This is their story.

0:00 Introduction
01:58 For the sake of my sisters
05:28 The danger of home schooling
07:16 Fleeing Taliban’s Afghanistan
10:30 Starting a new life in London
13:51 “Women are at home all the time”
16:10 Dars launch facing delays
20:06 Two years of educating in secret 
21:42 Dars is ready for launch
23:28 Raising awareness

snippet.title: Can putting a price on nature help us care about it more? - The Climate Question, BBC World Service
snippet.description:
Could giving nature a dollar value make us care about it more and help us fight against climate change?

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

Everyone who steps outside can appreciate the value that the natural world brings to our lives. To some people, the idea of placing a monetary value on trees and mangrove forests is wrong because nature and its gifts are priceless. But others say the love of nature has not stopped it from being polluted or destroyed.

The natural world plays a major role in capturing the carbon from our atmosphere. A marketplace now exists where countries and big business can pay others to protect their forests, swamps and bogs in return for offsetting their emissions.

The Climate Question asks whether putting a price on nature help us protect it?

Find more videos on climate change and the environment here: https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLz_B0PFGIn4dlFahw2svjb6-aW_BVOn4x

snippet.title: The township kid who took on the gold industry - Lives Less Ordinary, BBC World Service
snippet.description:
Apartheid taught Charles to know his place, so how did he end up suing the gold industry?

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

When Charles Abrahams told his teachers he was going to be a heart surgeon they laughed. This was Apartheid South Africa and kids like Charles had no business having such lofty ambitions. But Charles knew something those teachers didn't. He was destined for a bigger life and nobody was going to stand in his way. 
 
Charles has written a book, it's called Class Action: In Pursuit of a Larger Life.
 
TV Clip: Dallas, Leonard Katzman, Lorimar Productions
 
Presenter: Mobeen Azhar
Producer: Fiona Woods

Check out more extraordinary stories here: https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLz_B0PFGIn4fxldjnO2SAJ-Lg-owG7RR_

snippet.title: Sirimavo Bandaranaike: The world’s first woman prime minister - BBC World Service, Witness History
snippet.description:
Sirimavo Bandaranaike was elected the modern world’s first female head of government in 1960, when she became the prime minister of Sri Lanka, or Ceylon as it was known then.

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

She entered politics after the assassination of her husband just a year earlier.

Her daughter, Sunethra Bandaranaike tells Witness History about her mother’s ground-breaking political achievement.

snippet.title: Children of Ukrainian village orphaned by Russian missile - BBC World Service Documentaries
snippet.description:
A missile attack on the village of Hroza in October 2023, became one of the biggest single losses of civilian life in Ukraine since Russia’s full-scale invasion. Once a bustling community, Hroza is now a village of orphans. 

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

Fifty-nine people were killed in the strike. Not a single family was left untouched by this tragedy.

The BBC's Zhanna Bezpiatchuk investigates.

02:17 Valentyna's despair
03:43 'How can we abandon our children?'

snippet.title: How Putin’s influencers are profiting from Russia's war propaganda - BBC World Service Documentaries
snippet.description:
Russian pro-war influencers are generating big advertising revenues from their social media coverage of the conflict, the BBC’s Global Disinformation Team has found. 

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

Known in Russia as “Z Bloggers”, they embed with military units, share exclusive footage from the frontline, and call on young Russians to enlist in the army.

snippet.title: Indigenous peoples around the world, Global News Podcast - BBC World Service
snippet.description:
This special edition of the Global News Podcast will confront many of the challenges faced by indigenous peoples around the world, shining a spotlight on some of the indigenous leaders and activists, artists and academics who are working for change.

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

There are thousands of indigenous cultures, each with their own unique history and experience. No single person or story could ever speak for all of them. But for all their differences, there is also a common thread. Most indigenous peoples have been marginalised and persecuted by colonialism, imperialism and the modern governments that evolved out of those systems.

In some of the most developed countries on Earth, indigenous people continue to experience lower rates of health, education, employment and housing, and higher rates of violence and discrimination. This special edition of the Global News Podcast will confront many of those challenges. But most of all, it will shine a spotlight on some of the Indigenous leaders and activists, artists and academics who are working for change, while trying to preserve their culture and coexist equally alongside other communities. 

As well as hearing from some our our own indigenous and tribal listeners around the world, we also meet an Amazon tribe defending their land from illegal loggers; a Maori singer who makes pop music in his traditional language; Native American chefs bringing cultural foods to the restaurant scene.

snippet.title: Why we daydream and what goes on in our brain when we do - CrowdScience podcast, BBC World Service
snippet.description:
Why do we daydream and what goes on in our brain when our minds wander?

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

Have you ever been through a romantic break up, unable to shift the ex from your thoughts? You are, obviously, not alone. CrowdScience listener Elkin, experienced just that. But rather than wallowing in self-pity, he sought out an explanation.

So, presenter Alex Lathbridge puts on his thinking cap to find out what role daydreaming plays and whether anything can be done to stop it.

0:00 Introduction
2:40 Elkin wants to know why he daydreams so much and how to reduce it
4:39 How science defines daydreaming
6:03 Why we daydream and how much time on average we do it
6:56 Alex takes part in a seven day, daydreaming test
9:47 Are we in control of our daydreams? Here's what happening in our brain
12:56 How long does it take a thought to form?
16:05 Meet Taylor, she's a maladaptive daydreamer
16:46 What is maladaptive daydreaming?
22:04 How common is maladaptive daydreaming?
24:13 Alex takes part in an attention span experiment
26:09 Load theory or theory of attention
26:47 Activities to try to help you daydream less
28:45 Conclusion

From rethinking laziness to why we lie, discover more from our CrowdScience podcast here ➡️ https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLz_B0PFGIn4cT4qluPKNtMmBAPPrpoxvT

snippet.title: What is the Body Mass Index and is it the best measure of obesity? - CrowdScience, BBC World Service
snippet.description:
CrowdScience listener Maik wants to know what the Body Mass Index is and what his BMI score says about his body.

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

Maik trains dogs for a living and wonders if, like different breeds of dog, we simply have different body types?

So, Marnie Chesterton comes up with some answers, talking to doctors about how the BMI is used and misused in clinical practice, and looks at some alternative methods for measuring our body composition. She also sits down with philosopher Kate Manne to discuss the realities of living in a fatphobic world.

We hear from Tonga in the South Pacific, where high BMI scores have labelled the country highly obese. But this is not necessarily how Tongans see themselves.

And Marnie finds out if the BMI will continue to be used across the world as an important health marker to say whether people are healthy, overweight or obese, or whether it is destined for the scrap heap of medical history.

Watch more episodes of CrowdScience here 👉🏽 https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLz_B0PFGIn4cT4qluPKNtMmBAPPrpoxvT

00:00 How to calculate BMI
01:20 Listener Maik wants to know what BMI can tell you about your health?
02:20 How the WHO uses BMI to classify weight

06:40 What other kinds of health screening are there? Marnie enters the BodPod

17:20 BMI and access to health care

snippet.title: Covid denial to climate denial - BBC World Service, The Denial Files
snippet.description:
An online movement infected with extreme pandemic conspiracies is now peddling falsehoods about climate change in countries all around the world.

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

There are social media groups advocating that climate change is a “hoax” designed to limit our personal freedoms. And as debates over lockdowns and vaccines subside in many richer countries, they are looking for new territory, swapping in “climate science” for “Covid” in their viral conspiracy theories.

Researchers point out that a ready-made network of people who have fallen for misleading claims about global Covid-19 plots has created a receptive audience for lies about climate change.

Listen to more episodes of The Denial Files here: https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLz_B0PFGIn4cPiUQCISeRAkhh9g80XV0f

snippet.title: Brazil’s climate change disinformation war – BBC World Service, The Denial Files
snippet.description:
Brazil, where vast stretches of the Amazon rainforest have been cut down, has signed a pledge at COP26 to end deforestation by 2030. But do its leaders, including President Jair Bolsonaro, really believe in fighting climate change?
 
Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM
 
Influential voices in Brazil are spreading baseless conspiracy theories that man-made climate change is a hoax. President Jair Bolsonaro has labelled government agency scientists “bad Brazilians” after they produced data showing an alarming rate of deforestation in the Amazon.  
 
President Bolsonaro insists he is stepping up protection of the environment and has warned other countries not to meddle in Brazil’s internal affairs. Is the Amazon, one of the most important regions in the world for fighting climate change, safe in his hands?

Watch videos about COP26 here: https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLz_B0PFGIn4fO4sWHIt_ufEe1sJLBtUoe

Listen to the full series of The Denial Files: https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/w27vqf9y

snippet.title: Unrest in Baltimore and a tracking device - Bad Cops, Episode 1, BBC World Service podcast
snippet.description:
Civil unrest spreads across Baltimore after 25-year-old Freddie Gray dies in police custody. Meanwhile, a detective makes a troubling discovery when he arrests a major heroin dealer. It’s time to call in the FBI.

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

In Baltimore, Maryland, an elite group of plainclothes officers called the Gun Trace Task Force gets hundreds of illegal guns off the streets every year. Secretly, however, these detectives are also robbing people, selling drugs, planting evidence and framing innocent people. When some of the officers go too far, it triggers an FBI investigation that reveals the Gun Trace Task Force as one of the most corrupt police squads in American policing history. Jessica Lussenhop tells the story of the rise and fall of this once-powerful unit of officers, and its leader Sergeant Wayne Jenkins. And she asks: why do good cops go bad?

Bad Cops is a podcast from the BBC World Service
Written and presented by Jessica Lussenhop
Programme mixed by Neil Churchill
Additional mixing by James Beard
Producer: Ben Crighton
Editor: Richard Vadon

Trial exhibit photos provided by FBI / United States Attorney's Office (USAO).

Watch the series here: https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLz_B0PFGIn4cTxsknwvTYZPlpSOl0zApl

Listen/Download: https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/w13xtvk9/episodes/downloads

snippet.title: Brazil captain Roberta Moretti Avery on her cricketing passions - Stumped, BBC World Service
snippet.description:
England's Ben Stokes is out with an injury and Brazil women's captain Roberta Moretti Avery talks to us about development, captaincy and mental health.

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

On this week’s Stumped, Nikesh Rughani, Charu Sharma and Jim Maxwell look ahead to Sri Lanka’s three-match Test Series against England. The team discuss how much Stokes’ absence could have on the series and whether Ollie Pope is the right man to lead the side.

Plus, we speak to Brazil women’s captain Roberta Moretti Avery, who tells us about the growth of the sport in the country, what captaining her country means to her, and whether Brazil could compete in the World Cup in 2030.

snippet.title: Sri Lanka end 27 year wait for a ODI series victory over India - Stumped, BBC World Service
snippet.description:
It's the first time since 1997 that Sri Lanka have beaten India in a One Day International series.

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM  

Sri Lanka are celebrating after victory over India in the third One Day International by 110 runs to clinch the One Day series 2-0.

It's the first time since 1997 that Sri Lanka have beaten India in a One Day series. Alison Mitchell, Charu Sharma and Jim Maxwell reflect on the series and discuss Gautam Gambhir's tenure as India's Head Coach beginning in defeat.

The Hundred is ongoing in England with the business end of the tournament fast approaching. Australian cricketer Spencer Johnson who is part of the Oval Invincibles team, joins us to reflect on his experiences.

(00:00) Introduction
(01:38) Reflections on Sri Lanka’s ODI series win over India
(08:48) Interview with Oval Invincibles and Australia’s Spencer Johnson
(17:05) Goodbyes

snippet.title: The solar panel innovation supplying thousands with renewable energy - BBC World Service
snippet.description:
India relies heavily on fossil fuels like coal to generate electricity. The country's sunny weather makes it ideal for solar technologies, but land can be expensive and in limited supply.

Over the last few years, several companies have piloted a solution – covering stretches of canal in solar panels. 

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

Not only does the innovation minimise land use, the panels also reduce evaporation. But do the benefits outweigh the higher upfront costs? Researchers in California assess their potential.

snippet.title: COP26: Deforestation and how you can help - BBC World Service
snippet.description:
More than 100 world leaders have promised to end and reverse deforestation by 2030, at COP26. Could projects like this help achieve that target?

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

snippet.title: Talking to the Taliban - BBC World Service, A Wish for Afghanistan
snippet.description:

snippet.title: In the Taliban's inner circle from the very start - BBC World Service, A Wish for Afghanistan
snippet.description:
Founding member, ambassador, prisoner - in the Taliban's inner circle from the very start.

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM
All of our videos are subtitled and you can follow in many languages.

Abdul Salam Zaeef rose to prominence in the Taliban government that ruled Afghanistan until Western forces overthrew it following 9/11. Handed over to the Americans, Mullah Zaeef spent three years as a prisoner in the US detention centre, Guantanamo Bay. He no longer holds an official post in the Taliban, but he despises the democracy that has been built in Afghanistan over the last 20 years. He tells Lyse Doucet that Afghanistan needs a proper Islamic government.

Series music composed by Arson Fahim.

Hear more of the podcast: https://bbc.in/3h9jqRt

snippet.title: A shared gold medal in the men's Olympic high jump - BBC World Service
snippet.description:
🥇"I just asked him, 'can we have two golds?'"🥇

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

When the men's high jump at the Tokyo Olympics came down to a jump-off, Mutaz Essa Barshim and Gianmarco Tamberi decided to share a medal.

In doing so, they've made history - it was the first joint Olympic podium in athletics since 1912.

"We're competitive at the field and beyond that, it is just love and peace and sports is just a great tool that brings all of us together."

snippet.title: Why can't you sleep? - Deeply Human, BBC World Service
snippet.description:
Is insomnia really a problem of modern life... or is the struggle for sleep older than you think?

Subscribe - https://www.youtube.com/bbcworldservice

It's a common lament: this new world of smartphones and constant connectivity makes it nearly impossible to get enough sleep. But Shakespeare's characters were up all night, sleepwalking, and freaking out about their daily lives. Just how have our sleeping patterns really changed since the invention of the electric light?

Dessa dives deep into the science of sleep to find out what we need, what we're missing, and why it can be so hard to get a full night's rest.

Listen to the full episode here: https://www.bbc.co.uk/sounds/play/w3ct3hh5

snippet.title: Covid-19: India's child malnutrition crisis - BBC World Service
snippet.description:
An estimated 115 million children in India are said to be at risk of malnutrition. Experts say India's Covid lockdowns interrupted crucial government schemes that benefit hundreds of millions of women and children.

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

The malnutrition rates were already on the rise in the years leading up to the Covid outbreak. India’s lockdowns, some of the severest anywhere in the world, have made matters worse. In fact, recent reports indicate stunting among children in some areas has gone up by as much as 20% in a matter of just a few months.

Devina Gupta looks at the challenges and the measures being taken to tackle child malnutrition during a devastating pandemic.

Listen to more here: https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p09mtfmq

See more videos on India's Covid crisis: https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLz_B0PFGIn4cY6hsX_UlWATXksDJM9Zac

snippet.title: How is Covid impacting India's children? - BBC World Service
snippet.description:
Children in India are being hugely impacted by the coronavirus pandemic. In some cases where family members have been hospitalised, children are struggling to get basic care.

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

With nearly 470 million children, India has the world’s largest child population. Campaigners say millions of them have been seriously impacted by the pandemic, including their access to medical care, food, shelter, schooling, and even means of livelihood.

Many are facing severe mental trauma due to confinement and isolation at home, and a recent study says 577 were orphaned in less than two months during the second wave of the pandemic. Many children have also caught the virus, but thankfully complications have been rare.

The scale of the problem is daunting, but what can be done to ensure that children’s lives are not thrown into chaos?

More about the India Covid crisis here: https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLz_B0PFGIn4cY6hsX_UlWATXksDJM9Zac

localized.title: How is Covid impacting India's children? - BBC World Service
localized.description:
Children in India are being hugely impacted by the coronavirus pandemic. In some cases where family members have been hospitalised, children are struggling to get basic care.

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

With nearly 470 million children, India has the world’s largest child population. Campaigners say millions of them have been seriously impacted by the pandemic, including their access to medical care, food, shelter, schooling, and even means of livelihood.

Many are facing severe mental trauma due to confinement and isolation at home, and a recent study says 577 were orphaned in less than two months during the second wave of the pandemic. Many children have also caught the virus, but thankfully complications have been rare.

The scale of the problem is daunting, but what can be done to ensure that children’s lives are not thrown into chaos?

More about the India Covid crisis here: https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLz_B0PFGIn4cY6hsX_UlWATXksDJM9Zac

snippet.title: How hackers stole up to $14m from ATMs - The Lazarus Heist Season 2, Ep1 - BBC World Service podcast
snippet.description:
Millions of dollars are stolen from ATMs at the same time in 28 countries. An army of money mules stuff the cash into bags. Do they know who they are really working for?

Click here to subscribe to our channel 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

In just over two hours, the thieves take nearly $14 million - all from the accounts of Cosmos Bank in India. It's a technique known as jackpotting. The hackers are back!

In fact, the cyber criminals never went away. The Lazarus Heist Season 2 tells the story of the theft of billions of dollars around the globe. Investigators say a secretive, elite North Korean hacking ring is responsible. Nicknamed the Lazarus Group, it’s claimed they are becoming more ambitious, more audacious and more successful. North Korea says it has nothing to do with these cybercrimes, saying the United States is making these allegations to try and tarnish its image.

The Lazarus Heist podcast is presented by cybercrime investigative journalist Geoff White and veteran foreign correspondent and renowned North Korea expert Jean Lee.

Podcast producer: Vivien Jones

Watch the series here: https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLz_B0PFGIn4ccgXclIq9gdmf_nFNz-Og8

snippet.description:
Eighty-two-year-old Salme Nummela from Finland started practicing taekwondo in her 70s after accompanying her grandchildren to lessons.

Salme says taking up the martial art has improved her fitness and memory. The grandmother has now gone onto become the oldest known person in the world to earn a black belt in the sport. For her next challenge she wants to take up parachuting... Go Salme!

snippet.title: Women in Hollywood: Who runs the film industry? - The Conversation podcast, BBC World Service
snippet.description:
There was an impressive list of female creatives on this year's Oscar nominees list – actors, producers, costume designers - but no female directors.

Click here to subscribe 👉🏽 https://bbc.in/3VyyriM

In fact, in the Academy’s 94-year-history, only seven women have ever been nominated. Why is that? And what is getting in the way of achieving gender parity in filmmaking? Kim Chakanetsa travels to the heart of Hollywood to find out more.

Keri Putnam is a film executive and producer and the founder of Putnam Pictures. She served for 11 years as the CEO of the Sundance Institute which runs the Sundance Film Festival. Prior to that worked as a senior executive at Miramax and HBO. She is also the co-founder of Re-frame, an organisation providing mentorship and training to help women making it into the industry, and served three terms on the Women in Film Board of directors.

Stephanie Allain is a film Producer and writer and the newly-elected co-President of the Producers Guild of America, the first woman of colour to serve as PGA president. Stephanie was one of the original ReFrame ambassadors and served 3 terms on the WIF Board of Directors including nine years as Vice President. Stephanie was also the first Black woman to produce the Academy Awards in 2020. She runs her own company, Homegrown Pictures, which focuses on creating content by and about women and people of colour.

Check out more awesome women creating change here 👉🏽 https://bit.ly/3Wo1nu4

snippet.title: Death in Ice Valley - Episode 1: The Isdal Woman - @BBCWorldService
snippet.description:
An unidentified body in a cold, remote valley outside Bergen. Who was she? Why hasn't she been missed? 
 
Subscribe - https://www.youtube.com/bbcworldservice 
 
Some graves hold more secrets than others. This is the story of a woman travelling in Norway in 1970 who died a terrible death and left behind her a trail of strange clues. Her real identity has remained unknown for more than 50 years, and it is still one of the world's most intriguing unsolved mysteries. 
 
Death in Ice Valley is an original podcast series made by the BBC World Service and NRK. It's presented by Marit Higraff and Neil McCarthy. 
 
This episode was first broadcast in April 2018. Some details and information on the case that subsequently came to light are covered in later episodes.
 
Sound design: Phil Channell 
Additional investigation: Ståle Hansen and Øyvind Bye Skille from NRK 
Series editor: Philip Sellars 
BBC World Service editor: Jon Manel Podcast studio mixed by Donald MacDonald 
Death in Ice Valley is written and produced by Neil McCarthy 
 
Join the conversation: #DeathinIceValley www.facebook.com/groups/deathinicevalley 
 
There's more information on our website, and you can listen again and download the podcast: https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p060ms2h  

You can also discuss what you've been hearing and help to solve the mystery in our dedicated Facebook group https://www.facebook.com/groups/deathinicevalley/

snippet.title: Bangladesh: Stick-wielding students clash with Sheikh Hasina supporters on National Mourning Day
snippet.description:
Bangladesh Crisis: Dozens of protesters, part of the student-led movement that ousted Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina, gathered in Dhaka on Thursday to prevent rallies by her supporters on the former public holiday of National Mourning Day. The day, which marks the assassination of Hasina's father, Sheikh Mujibur Rahman, in 1975, saw tensions flare as students wielding sticks and flags clashed with individuals they believed were Hasina supporters. The protests, which initially targeted employment quotas, have claimed around 300 lives and led to the appointment of an interim government led by Nobel laureate Muhammad Yunus to oversee upcoming elections.

#BangladeshNews #SheikhMujiburRahman #Bangladesh #SheikhHasina

snippet.description:
Tripura Flood: The flood situation in Tripura deteriorated further on Wednesday, with the death toll rising to 10. Chief Minister Manik Saha provided updates on the crisis, noting that two others were injured and more than 34,000 people have been displaced. The state has established around 346 relief camps to provide shelter for those affected. The government continues to monitor the situation closely as efforts are made to provide relief and assistance to the flood-hit regions.

snippet.title: Kolkata Doctor Case: WB Government Removes RG Kar Principal Suhrita Paul And Other Senior Officials
snippet.description:
Kolkata Doctor Case: Following weeks of protests by junior doctors at Kolkata's RG Kar Medical College and Hospital over the rape and murder of a colleague, the West Bengal government has responded by removing three senior officials from their positions. Dr. Bulbul Mukhopadhyay, the medical superintendent and vice-principal, has been replaced by Saptarshi Chatterjee. Suhrita Paul, recently appointed as the college principal, has also been removed, with Manas Kumar Bandyopadhyay taking over. Additionally, Dr. Arunabha Datta Chaudhuri has been transferred to Malda Medical College, and Dr. Sandeep Ghosh's appointment as principal of Calcutta National Medical College has been cancelled, meeting the demands of the protesting doctors.

snippet.title: Water Scarcity: How 'Direct Portable Reuse' Method Is Beneficial To Save Water
snippet.description:
Water Scarcity: Water scarcity poses a significant challenge globally due to population growth, industrialization, and inadequate wastewater treatment. In response, there’s a growing need to rethink water management and shift toward a fit-for-purpose approach. snippet.title: Ram Mandir: Sculptor of Ram Lalla Idol, Arun Yogiraj, Mobbed With Adulation At Bengaluru Airport
snippet.description:
Ram Mandir: Arun Yogiraj, the sculptor behind the Ram Lalla idol for the Ram Temple in Ayodhya, experienced an overwhelming reception at Bengaluru airport as he arrived at the Kempegowda International Airport. A massive crowd, including enthusiastic BJP workers, surrounded Arun Yogiraj, garlanding him and showering flowers. The air resonated with chants of 'Jai Sri Ram' and 'Long Live Yogiraj,' showcasing the fervent admiration for the sculptor of the iconic Ram Lalla idol.

snippet.description:
Maldives Controversy: Ibrahim Shaheeb, the High Commissioner of the Republic of Maldives, visited the Parliament in Delhi on the first day of the Budget session, addressing India's fastest-growing economy and the diplomatic ties between India and Maldives. The envoy's visit comes in the midst of escalating tensions, with Gasuim Ibrahim, leader of the Jumhoori Party, urging Maldives President Mohamed Muizzu to issue a formal apology to India and Prime Minister Narendra Modi. This appeal follows President Muizzu's earlier remarks, deemed pro-China, where he indirectly referred to India as a bully. The diplomatic strain originated from derogatory social media posts by Maldivian ministers against PM Modi, leading to a call for impeachment by the main opposition party, Maldivian Democratic Party (MDP).

snippet.title: INDIA Alliance Protest: Rahul Gandhi Attributes Parliament Security Breach to Unemployment
snippet.description:
INDIA Alliance Protest: During the INDIA Alliance protest held at Jantar Mantar, Congress leader Rahul Gandhi addressed the crowd, highlighting the incident where a few youth breached security in Parliament, releasing smoke, prompting BJP MPs to flee. Rahul Gandhi pointed out that while the security breach was a concern, the underlying reason for such an action was the prevalent issue of unemployment in the country. Rahul Gandhi emphasized the link between the incident and the broader problem of joblessness, suggesting that the frustration arising from unemployment might have been a contributing factor to the protest's unconventional method within the parliamentary premises.

snippet.title: Mumbai Remembers 26/11 Terror Attacks on 15th Anniversary; Enhanced Security Measures Launched
snippet.description:
26/11 Mumbai Attack: As Mumbai commemorates the 15th anniversary of the 26/11 terror attacks, tributes pour in for the 160 lives lost and over 300 injured. Maharashtra Chief Minister Eknath Shinde and Deputy Chief Minister Devendra Fadnavis pay homage at the police headquarters. Mumbai Police, reflecting on the tragic event, intensified security efforts with 24/7 patrolling of identified vulnerable coastal points, new quick-response police teams, and drone surveillance. Despite the acquisition of 46 high-speed boats, concerns arise as 38 are reported to be non-functional, underscoring the ongoing challenges in maintaining coastal security.

snippet.title: MP CM Oath Ceremony: Mohan Yadav Takes Oath As MP CM, Rajendra Shukla, Jagdish Devda As Dy CMs
snippet.description:
MP CM Oath Ceremony: In a historic ceremony at Bhopal's Lal Parade Ground, Mohan Yadav assumed the role of Madhya Pradesh Chief Minister, accompanied by his deputies Rajendra Shukla and Jagdish Devda. The former education minister and three-time MLA from Ujjain South, Yadav brings a wealth of experience to the state's leadership. Notably, Devda, representing the Scheduled Caste (SC), and Shukla, a prominent Brahmin figure in the Vindhya Pradesh region, add diverse perspectives to the leadership team. The swearing-in ceremony was a grand affair with attendance from political luminaries, including Prime Minister Narendra Modi, Union Home Minister Amit Shah, Uttar Pradesh Chief Minister Yogi Adityanath, and Maharashtra CM Eknath Shinde. Following the oath-taking in Bhopal, the political entourage is set to head to Raipur, marking the commencement of this new era in Madhya Pradesh's governance.

Yadav, a father of three with a diverse academic background, brings a wealth of experience and qualifications, holding degrees in BSc, LLB, MA, MBA, and PhD.

snippet.title: Chhattisgarh CM Oath Ceremony: Amit Shah In Raipur For Vishnu Deo Sai Swearing In Ceremony
snippet.description:
Chhattisgarh CM Oath Ceremony: Union Home Minister Amit Shah and BJP National President JP Nadda make a high-profile entrance in Raipur, marking their presence at the much-anticipated swearing-in ceremony of Chhattisgarh CM-designate Vishnu Deo Sai. Following an electoral triumph for the BJP, securing 163 seats after battling two decades of incumbency, the stage is set for a grand celebration. A robust security detail of around 1,000 police personnel has been deployed for the event. Ahead of the ceremony, Vishnu Deo Sai sought divine blessings at the Jagannath Temple in Raipur. The inauguration of Chhattisgarh's Chief Minister and his council of ministers is slated to take place today in Raipur, symbolizing a new era for the state.

localized.description:
Chhattisgarh CM: Ending days of speculation, the BJP has officially declared former Union Minister Vishnu Deo Sai as the new Chief Minister of Chhattisgarh. Known as one of the most senior tribal leaders in the state, Sai's appointment follows the BJP's significant electoral victory in a notable turnaround from 2018. The 59-year-old leader, a four-time Lok Sabha MP and former Union Minister, is expected to bring his experience to the forefront in the new role.

snippet.description:

The attack follows an Israeli strike on Tuesday that killed one and wounded 19. This escalation comes amid ongoing U.S. diplomatic efforts to broker a cease-fire in the Gaza conflict, which continue to face challenges.

snippet.description:

Antony Blinken, sent by President Joe Biden, stressed the urgency of concluding the agreement while preventing any actions that could escalate the conflict or derail the process.

snippet.title: Parliament Session: Women's Reservation Bill Passed In Rajya Sabha With 215 Votes | Sansad
snippet.description:
Parliament Session: The Rajya Sabha achieved a historic milestone on Thursday as it passed the Constitution (One Hundred and Twenty-Eighth Amendment) Bill, 2023, which mandates the reservation of one-third of seats for women in the Lok Sabha and state Assemblies. Following extensive debates and discussions among Members of Parliament from various political parties, the Bill secured resounding support, with a total of 215 votes in favor and none against it. Prime Minister Narendra Modi, in his concluding remarks on the Bill, expressed optimism about its potential to instill newfound confidence in the nation's citizens and underscored the positive collaborative efforts of all political parties in advancing women's empowerment. This legislative accomplishment represents a significant stride toward gender equality in Indian politics.

snippet.title: Women Reservation Bill Clears Rajya Sabha After Lok Sabha With Unanimous Support
snippet.description:
The Women's Reservation Bill, also known as Nari Shakti Vandan Adhiniyam, has achieved unanimous approval in the Rajya Sabha, marking successful passage in both houses of Parliament. The bill ensures 33% reservation for women in the parliament, and Prime Minister Narendra Modi, in his concluding remarks on the bill, emphasized its potential to boost confidence and women's empowerment, highlighting the positive bipartisan efforts behind its passage.

snippet.title: G20 Summit 2023: US State Dept. Praises G20's Success Despite Russia Omission in Declaration
snippet.description:
G20 Summit 2023: According to US State Department Spokesperson Matthew Miller, the G20 Summit was indeed successful, despite the absence of the word "Russia" from the New Delhi Leaders' Declaration. He emphasized the complexity of the G20, highlighting that both Russia and China are members with diverse perspectives. Miller stressed the significance of the organization's ability to issue a statement calling for the respect of territorial integrity and sovereignty, and the condemnation of any violation of these principles. He viewed this statement as crucial because it directly addresses the core issues surrounding Russia's invasion of Ukraine, making it a vital and important stance taken by the G20.

snippet.description:
Aditya L1 Mission: Aditya-L1, India’s first solar observatory, was successfully placed in the final orbit, its desired destination from where it will make observations of the Sun for the next five years. Aditya-L1 was successfully inserted into the Larange Point 1, one of the five locations in the Earth-Sun system where the gravitational effects of the two roughly cancel each other out. It is a relatively stable point for a spacecraft to be parked, and make observations of the Sun.

snippet.title: PM Modi Highlights Chandrayaan 3 Success And Global Role Ahead Of Special Parliamentary Session
snippet.description:
Parliament Special Session: PM Narendra Modi addressed the media outside Parliament in anticipation of the special session scheduled to commence at 11 am. During his interaction, PM Modi lauded India's achievement in the successful Moon mission, Chandrayaan-3, and reflected on the recently concluded G20 Summit held in the national capital. PM Modi emphasized India's growing prominence as a leading advocate for the Global South, particularly highlighting the inclusion of the African Union in the G20 discussions. PM Modi referred to the upcoming special session as "short but significant." The Prime Minister is set to inaugurate the special parliament session with a speech in the Lok Sabha at 11 am.

snippet.title: Cyclone Biparjoy: Heavy Rains In Ajmer Causes Water Logging At Hospital In Ajmer
snippet.description:
Cyclone Biparjoy: Medical service in Jawaharlal Nehru Hospital in Ajmer came to a halt as heavy rains that lashed the city on June 18 caused waterlogging at the hospital premises. Ajmer has been witnessing heavy rain since June 18 morning as an effect of Cyclone Biparjoy. Meanwhile, restoration work has begun in Mandvi as the cyclone passes Gujarat.

snippet.title: Sikkim Rain: More Than 2,400 Tourists Stranded In North Sikkim Due To Inclement Weather
snippet.description:
Sikkim Rain: More than 2,400 tourists, including 60 college students were stranded in Lachen and Lachung area of North Sikkim district due to road blockades following incessant rainfall since the last three days, officials said on Saturday. As of now, three buses and two other vehicles carrying 123 tourists have left for the state capital Gangtok.

snippet.title: This Cancer Survivor Is Now A Gym Instructor
snippet.description:
Govind Rawat, 31, battled acute myeloid leukemia and decided to open a fitness centre and devise routines for cancer survivors too. After medication and supplements for a year, Govind was declared cancer-free in March 2022. He quit his family business to open his fitness studio. “My body has never been this good, so always live on your terms,” says the cancer survivor, whom neighbors have now christened Mr. Narela.

snippet.title: Manipur Violence: Wife of Kuki Ex-MLA Dies in Manipur Bomb Blast at Their Residence
snippet.description:
Manipur Violence: Charubala Haokip, the wife of former Saikul MLA Yamthong Haokip, died after a bomb exploded at their home in Manipur’s Kangpokpi district, police said on Sunday.
Charubala Haokip, 59, was from the Meitei community and lived in Ekou Mulam in the Kuki-Zomi-dominated Kangpokpi district. Yamthong Haokip, 64, had won the Saikul seat twice, in 2012 and 2017, both times on a Congress ticket. He switched to the BJP before the 2022 Assembly elections.

snippet.title: Manipur Violence: 3 Killed in Gunfight Between Kuki Groups in Manipur's Tengnoupal District
snippet.description:
Manipur Violence: A gunfight between armed Kuki-Zo villagers and the United Kuki Liberation Front (UKLF) in Manipur's Tengnoupal district resulted in three deaths on Friday morning, though police have yet to recover any bodies. The clash, which occurred near the state capital Imphal, is believed to have been fueled by tensions over control of trade routes. The UKLF claimed it was attacked by members of the same community, accusing them of collaborating with Meiteis. The incident comes amidst a recent lull in violence between the Meitei and Kuki communities.

snippet.title: Arvind Kejriwal Arrest: AAP's Jasmine Shah Accuses CBI of False Statements in Court
snippet.description:
Arvind Kejriwal Arrest: AAP leader Jasmine Shah accused the CBI of lying in court, stating, "CBI has been exposed in front of the country. Today the CBI was caught red-handed for giving a false statement inside the court." Shah claimed the CBI falsely asserted that Arvind Kejriwal blamed Manish Sisodia for Delhi's excise policy. "Arvind Kejriwal himself stood up and said that the CBI was lying. Arvind Kejriwal is innocent, Manish Sisodia is innocent, and the entire Aam Aadmi Party is innocent," Jasmine Shah declared.

snippet.title: "An Irreparable Loss"; Sakshi Malik's Mother Voices Concern Over Wrestler's Retirement
snippet.description:
Sudesh Malik, the mother of Olympic medalist wrestler Sakshi Malik, expressed profound sorrow and disappointment following Sakshi's decision to step away from the sport. Sudesh lamented the situation as an irreparable loss, citing the lack of resolution despite Sakshi's 40-day protest for justice. She highlighted the potential impact on younger girls in the wrestling community, fearing their disheartenment witnessing Sakshi's struggle for justice. Sudesh emphasized Sakshi's relentless dedication, mentioning her rigorous training for an Olympic gold medal, and acknowledged the time it might take for Sakshi to recover from this distressing experience.
